                <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-gray-900 leading-tight">The Big Data Breach: When Technical Failures Become Governance Failures</h1>
                <p class="text-md text-gray-500 mt-2">Published: September 1, 2025 by The Integrity Protocol</p>
            </div>

            <div class="article-content border-t pt-8">
                <h2>Case Summary: Exposed Data</h2>
                <p>In September 2022, one of Australia's largest telco's suffered a major data breach affecting nearly 10 million customers. Personal details (names, addresses, birth dates, phone numbers, passport/driver's license info) were exposed. The breach stemmed from an exposed API (a gateway for data) that did not require authentication.</p>

                <h2>The Integrity Gap: Where Did Things Break Down?</h2>
                <p>The failure was multi-layered, highlighting gaps across the entire organisation:</p>
                <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 ml-4">
                    <li><strong>Technical Integrity:</strong> Sensitive customer data was sitting behind an API without proper authenticationâ€”like leaving the vault door ajar.</li>
                    <li><strong>Organisational Integrity:</strong> The telco claimed to follow "best practice security," but the breach revealed a profound gap between policy on paper and controls in practice.</li>
                    <li><strong>Governance Integrity:</strong> Responsibility was diffused. Who inside the telco owned the risk? Who was accountable for enforcing data minimisation and security?</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="mt-4">This is the heart of governance: security isn't just about firewalls; it's about aligning responsibility, accountability, and action across the board.</p>
                
